The variable selected to this visualization task is Carbon Dioxide Emissions embodied in International Trade (Environment > Air and climate > Carbon Dioxide Emissions embodied in International Trade) from the OECD website.

The file has been filtered by considering only World partnerships and the Total value, that is to say the first 1037 rows of the dataset; afterwards 12 countries have been selected in order to make the visualizations understandable.

a) One variable plot: using the quantity you have selected show its distribution for all countries (all together and with facetting)

carbon <- read.csv("C:/Users/fra12/Desktop/Francesca/UC3M/Network Analysis and Data Visualization/HW3/carbon (2).csv")
data<-carbon[,c(4,9,17)]
dataAll<-data[1:1037,]

filter <- which(dataAll$Country== "Australia" | dataAll$Country== "Costa Rica" | dataAll$Country=="United Kingdom" | dataAll$Country=="Korea" | dataAll$Country=="Germany" | dataAll$Country=="France" | dataAll$Country=="Japan" | dataAll$Country=="Iceland" | dataAll$Country=="Russia" | dataAll$Country =="United States" | dataAll$Country=="India" | dataAll$Country=="Canada")

data <-dataAll[filter,]               
attach(data)
summary(data)
##        Country         TIME          Value       
##  Australia : 17   Min.   :1995   Min.   : 0.808  
##  Canada    : 17   1st Qu.:1999   1st Qu.: 6.510  
##  Costa Rica: 17   Median :2003   Median : 9.309  
##  France    : 17   Mean   :2003   Mean   : 9.716  
##  Germany   : 17   3rd Qu.:2007   3rd Qu.:12.943  
##  Iceland   : 17   Max.   :2011   Max.   :19.998  
##  (Other)   :102
ggplot(data,aes(x=Value,col=Country)) + geom_density()  + theme(legend.title=element_text(face="bold"),legend.key.width=unit(0.5,"cm"),legend.key.height=unit(0.5,"cm"),legend.position = "top", legend.justification = "right") + labs(x = "Carbon Dioxide Emissions", y = "Density")

ggplot(data,aes(x=Value, col=Country)) + geom_density(show.legend = F) + theme_light(base_size=30)  + labs(x = "Carbon Dioxide Emissions", y="Density") +  facet_wrap(~Country, ncol=4, shrink = F)

b) Two variable plot:

a) Show the evolution of a quantity as a function of time for all countries

ggplot(data) +geom_line(aes(x=TIME, y= Value,col=Country))  + theme(legend.title=element_text(face="bold"),legend.key.width=unit(0.5,"cm"),legend.key.height=unit(0.5,"cm"),legend.position = "top", legend.justification = "right") + labs(x = "Years", y = "Carbon Dioxide Emissions")

b) Overlay a smoothing average.

ggplot(data,aes(x=TIME, y= Value,col=Country)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth()+theme(legend.title=element_text(face="bold"),legend.key.width=unit(0.5,"cm"),legend.key.height=unit(0.5,"cm"),legend.position = "top", legend.justification = "right") + labs(x = "Years", y = "Carbon Dioxide Emissions")

c) Use facetting to show the same visualization per country

ggplot(data,aes(x=TIME,y=Value,col=Country))+geom_point() + geom_smooth(SE=T)  + labs(x = "Years", y = "Carbon Dioxide Emissions (tot)") + facet_wrap(~Country, ncol=4) + theme_light(base_size=30) + theme(legend.position = "none")+ labs(x = "Years", y = "Carbon Dioxide Emissions")

c) Gapminder bubble plot:

a) Get also the population per country and year

population<- read.csv("C:/Users/fra12/Desktop/Francesca/UC3M/Network Analysis and Data Visualization/HW3/POP_FIVE_HIST_04062018145058127.csv")

filter<-which(population$SEX=="TT" & population$Unit=="Persons" & population$SUBJECT=="YP99TLL1_ST" & population$TIME > 1999)
pop<-population[filter,c(2, 10,17)]

b) Merge the data and produce a bubble plot in which you visualize population as a function of the quantity for each year (use facetting)

colnames(pop)[2] = "TIME"
colnames(pop)[3] = "Population"
merged<-merge(data, pop, by = c("TIME","Country"))
head(merged)
##   TIME   Country  Value Population
## 1 2000 Australia 17.470   19029000
## 2 2000    Canada 17.208   30685730
## 3 2000    France  6.395   59062380
## 4 2000   Germany  9.932   82211500
## 5 2000   Iceland  7.614     281154
## 6 2000     India  0.938 1042262000
ggplot(merged) + geom_point(aes(x=Country,y=Value,size=Population, col=Country)) + scale_size_continuous(range = c(1, 10)) + theme(legend.title=element_text(face="bold"),legend.position = "top", legend.justification = "center", axis.title.x = element_blank(), axis.text.x = element_blank()) + facet_wrap(~TIME, ncol=2) + labs(y = "Carbon Dioxide Emissions") + geom_text(aes(x=Country,y=Value-1.20, label=Country,col=Country, size=Population), show.legend = F) + scale_size_continuous(range = c(2,5)) + guides(col = FALSE)
